to Diane (NN)-  I'm sending this email in follow-up to the last two USEPA-NNEPA conference calls regarding LUST sites within the Navajo Nation.  During those calls, I explained my understanding of the status of the former Garnenez Trading Post (NAV-444).  Based on my file review, there is no solid evidence that USTs ever existed at this site.  The USEPA Region 9 memo-to-file dated 7/26/04 (included in the attachment below) indicates that highway widening in 1975 may have removed any previous UST or AST systems.  In addition, the same USEPA memo refers to a 1976 Tribal Resolution banning future oil and gas sales at this site.  When Arthur Boone (formerly with USEPA) visited the site in 2000, he was informed that only ASTs had been used at the site, or that any previous USTs had been floated out during flooding of the San Juan River.

iina ba's October 2008 Geophysical Investigation Report noted that no USTs were identified during the geophysical survey and, as such, recommended "no further action" (see attachment).  USEPA Region 9 originally considered this a "suspected release" site.  However, based on the information discussed above, USEPA has removed this site from its LUST universe.  If hydrocarbon contamination is discovered at this site in the future, USEPA may reopen the file.  Please contact me with an questions.
"

During the post-remediation, verification soil sampling on 3/13/08, the soil sample from 10 feet bgs had a 120 mg/kg naphthalene concentration, which was above the current 3.8 mg/kg residential RSL for naphthalene. The maximum TPH-gas concentration (47,000 mg/kg) was also found in the soil sample from 10 feet bgs.
On 10/20/14, the soil sample from 10 feet bgs in the area of the former product piping had detectable ORO (510 mg/kg) and DRO (40 mg/kg).

On 8/19/10, the soil sample from 14 feet bgs below the former northwestern dispenser had detectable GRO (490 mg/kg) and ORO (1,100 mg/kg). On 9/1/10, the soil sample from 30 feet bgs in this same area had a 20 mg/kg naphthalene concentration, which was above the current 17 mg/kg industrial RSL for naphthalene (the Site is still an active UST facility). On 8/28/12, the bis(2-ethylhexyl)phthalate concentration in monitoring well MW-3 was 7.6 ug/l, which was slightly above its 6 ug/l MCL.
Report date is 9/30/2011 when field work was conducted on 10/14/2011.  The report date might be 2012.

6 soil samples were collected from below the 2 UST systems at the Site and VOCs, PAHs, TPH (gas, diesel & oil), and total lead were analyzed. The only organic compound detected was benzo(g,h,i)perylene at 0.028 mg/kg (no EPA RSL exists for this compound). The only lead concentration above Region 9's 80 mg/kg screening level was the sample from below the dispenser, which had a 135 mg/kg total lead concentration. LND-4-3 management's opinion was that the source of this lead concentration was unknown given the near absence of hydrocarbon detections in the soil samples. The soil in the area of the former dispenser is currently below a concrete sidewalk, and the business at the Site is still an active car dealership/auto maintenance facility.
